                <section class="exc-content">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="exc-container">
                                                                                                        <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How To Do</h2>
                                    <ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stand between a set of parallel dip bars. Hold them with an overhand grip in line with your torso.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Raise yourself up so your arms are locked and your body is supported. A box or a suitable raised surface can also used to help. Bend your knees and cross your feet over each other.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Slide your body forward so your chest is in front of your shoulders.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Tilt your body forward so that it is at about a 30-degree angle to the floor.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Take a deep breath in and engage your core. Bend at the elbows to lower your body toward the floor. Lower yourself until your upper arms are parallel to the ground.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pause at the bottom position. Push back to the start position while taking a breath out.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pause momentarily in the top position and then move into the next rep.</span></li></ol>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Tips From Expert</h2>
                                    <ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Keep your shoulder blades pulled back. This will prevent rounding your shoulders which will take the emphasis off your chest in the bottom position.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do not push up to a vertical torso position. Maintain the angled torso position throughout the entire movement.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Rather than pushing down with your hands as you come up, push your elbows in while squeezing your biceps. This will increase chest activation by providing adduction, moving the chest fibers toward the body's midline.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the momentary pause in the top position, squeeze the handles inward. This creates isometric chest adduction, meaning your chest muscles contract without moving.</span></li></ul>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Optimal Sets and Reps</h2>
                                    <p>Our programming table shows the optimum set and rep combinations for various training objectives.</p>                                                                                <div style="overflow: auto">
                                                <figure class="wp-block-table">
                                                    <table>
                                                        <thead>
                                                            <tr>
                                                                <th>Training Type</th>
                                                                <th>Sets</th>
                                                                                                                                    <th>Reps</th>
                                                                                                                            </tr>
                                                        </thead>
